{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17520719","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17520719"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:28:02+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:28:02+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13431"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13431","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13431"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.06,0.55,0.08,0.24]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6039"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102111"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6039","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6039"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13431"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84568"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"349"},{"type":"tags","id":"1240"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"11020"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11886"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12004"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13997"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16503"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35490"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35519"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102111","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/102111"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 24-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-day history of vaginal itchiness, burning on urination and a change in her vaginal secretions. She has not experienced flank or pelvic pain, fevers, change in colour or frequency of urination, intermenstrual bleeding, post-coital bleeding or pain during intercourse. Her medical history includes a recent ear infection treated with amoxicillin. She has no other significant medical history. She has a subcutaneous contraceptive implant and is sexually active with one male partner. She reports an allergy to fluconazole but does not take any regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well. Her pulse rate is 86/min, blood pressure 112/74 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.7\u00b0C. Pelvic examination reveals notable discomfort on insertion of the speculum, and a white, non-odorous discharge is seen.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Fluconazole 150 mg orally, once","Trimethoprim 300 mg orally, for three days","Clotrimazole 1% vaginal cream intravaginally, once nightly for six nights","Clindamycin 300 mg orally, twice daily for seven days","Nystatin 100,000 units/5 g vaginal cream intravaginally, once nightly for 14 nights"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient\u0027s presentation is consistent with vaginal candidiasis. The white, non-odorous discharge, associated with dysuria but no increase in urinary frequency, is typical of a candida infection. Recent antibiotic use for her ear infection is a significant risk factor for candidiasis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EClotrimazole 1% vaginal cream\u003C/strong\u003E applied intravaginally once nightly for six nights is the most appropriate treatment. It is the first-line management for uncomplicated vaginal candidiasis, including in patients with a reported allergy to fluconazole, as outlined in the Australian Therapeutic Guidelines.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFluconazole\u003C/strong\u003E orally is another alternate treatment for vaginal candidiasis after intravaginal azole creams or pessaries. However, this patient reports an allergy to fluconazole, making it an inappropriate choice.  In reality, most patients prefer the single oral tablet as easier to take though the cream can also give symptomatic relief.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETrimethoprim\u003C/strong\u003E is used for treating uncomplicated acute cystitis, which is not the likely diagnosis given the patient\u0027s symptoms and examination findings.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EClindamycin\u003C/strong\u003E is typically used for bacterial vaginosis, which is characterised by a thin, grey, homogeneous discharge with a fishy odour, unlike the presentation in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENystatin\u003C/strong\u003E vaginal cream is less effective than azole antifungals for candidiasis but may be considered as a second-line option if clotrimazole is not tolerated or unavailable.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile candidiasis is the most likely diagnosis given the recent antibiotic use and clinical presentation, it\u0027s important to offer screening opportunistically for sexually transmitted infections such as chlamydia and gonorrhoea, as their symptoms can overlap with those of candidiasis. \u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Recent antibiotic use is a risk factor for vaginal candidiasis.","Topical clotrimazole is the first-line treatment for uncomplicated vaginal candidiasis in patients (especially if the patient has a fluconazole allergy)","Opportunistic screening for sexually transmitted infections is important even when candidiasis is suspected."],"references":["Vaginal discharge. In Australian STI guidelines [Internet]. [cited 2024 Feb 27]. Available at: https://sti.guidelines.org.au/syndromes/vaginal-discharge/","Candida vulvovaginitis in adult females. In Electronic therapeutic guidelines complete. 2022; Retrieved August 11, 2024. Available at: https://tgldcdp.tg.org.au/etgcomplete"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84568"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13431"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84568","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/84568"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-07T23:38:11+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-07T23:39:43+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6039"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102111"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"22","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/22"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf53","name":"Gynaecology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagG